title: Raster analysis of cetacean species richness off the California Bight
description: Project completed for an assignment in Allison Horst's ESM 244 class.
contents:
Introduction
This analysis- with associated Rmarkdown file– explores cetacean species richness of the area off the coast of the California Bight. The presence or absence of the 35 species of cetaceans was calculated using a raster of values associated with the probability of occurrence for each species. These values were captured from analysis by Kaschner, et al. and are relative to species-specific environmental suitability based on water temperature, depth, salinity, and distance to land. The extent of the analysis was constrained to 125°W to 115°W and 32°N to 38°N. Data: Kaschner et al. (2016). Aquamaps.org.


hide

#read in data
cetaceans <- list.files(path = here('_posts/2021-03-14-cetacean/data/ca_cetaceans'), full.names = TRUE, pattern = ".tif")

#stack the raster files
ca_cetaceans <- stack(cetaceans)

#transform crs
proj4string(ca_cetaceans) <- "+proj=utm +zone=10 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0"





hide

#create function to reclassify the raster to a binary (threshhold value = 0.6)
is_present <- function(x, thresh = 0.6) {
  y <- ifelse(x >= thresh, 1, 0)
  return(y)
}

#run function over raster stack
cet_presence <- calc(ca_cetaceans, fun = is_present)

#plot presence for each species individually
#plot(cet_presence, col = c('red', 'green4'))

#sum the rasters to reclassify values by richness
cet_density <- calc(cet_presence, fun = sum, na.rm = TRUE)





hide

#richness raster
plot(cet_density)




Figure 1: Figure 1: Species richness raster for 35 species of cetaceans off the coast of the California Bight. Threshhold value for presence was set at 0.6 probability of occurrence for each species. Data: Kaschner et al. (2016). Aquamaps.org.





hide

#download shapefiles
coast <- ne_download(scale = "large", type = 'land', category = 'physical', returnclass = "sf")
states <- ne_download(scale = "large", type = 'states', category = 'cultural', returnclass = "sf")





hide

#filter shapefile for CA
ca <- states %>% 
  filter(name == "California")

#turn raster into a df
cet_density_df <- raster::rasterToPoints(cet_density) %>%
  as.data.frame()

#create a ggplot map of richness
ggplot() +
  geom_raster(data = cet_density_df, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = layer)) +
  scale_fill_distiller(type = "seq", palette = "Blues", aesthetics = "fill", direction = 1) +
  geom_sf(data = coast, fill = "darkgrey") +
  geom_sf(data = ca, fill = "darkgrey") +
  coord_sf(xlim = c(-125, -115), ylim = c(32,38), expand = FALSE) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = NULL, fill = "Cetacean Richness")




Figure 2: Figure 2: Map of species richness for 35 species of cetaceans off the coast of the California Bight. Threshhold value for presence was set at 0.6 probability of occurence. Data: Kaschner et al. (2016). Aquamaps.org.



Data Citations
Kaschner, K., Rius-Barile, J., Kesner-Reyes, K., Garilao, C., Kullander, S., Rees, T., & Froese, R. (2016). AquaMaps: Predicted range maps for aquatic species. www.aquamaps.org

title: A graphical representation of changing water levels in California's Mono Lake, 1850-2017
description: Project completed for an assignment in Allison Horst's ESM 206 class.
contents:
hide

#read in data
mono_lake <- read.csv(here("_posts/2021-03-14-mono-lake/", "mono_lake_annual_levels.csv"), skip = 5) %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  mutate(event = case_when(
    year == 1941 ~ "1941 - LA DWP begins diverting water",
    year == 1994 ~ "1994 - Decision 1631 sets \nlake level of 6,392 ft \nto protect Mono Lake"
  ))

#reticulating splines
splines <- as.data.frame(spline(mono_lake$year, mono_lake$lake_level_feet_above_sea_level))

#visualize data
ggplot(data = mono_lake, aes(x = year, y = lake_level_feet_above_sea_level)) +
  geom_line(data = splines, aes(x = x, y = y), size = 1, color = "royalblue4") +
  geom_ribbon(data = mono_lake, aes(ymin = -Inf, ymax = lake_level_feet_above_sea_level), fill = "royalblue", alpha = .2) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = 6350, ymax = 6360), fill = "darkorange", alpha = .3) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = -Inf, ymax = 6350), fill = "darkorange", alpha = .5) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 6360, color = "darkorange", size = 1, linetype = "longdash") +
  annotate("text", x = 1855, y = 6363,
           label = "6,360 ft - Water salinity above 120 g/L leads to decreased food supply for grebes and gulls",
           hjust = 0, size = 3, fontface = "bold") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 6377, color = "goldenrod2", size = 1) +
  annotate("text", x = 1855, y = 6380,
           label = "6,377 ft - Emergence of land bridges leads to bird predation at nesting sites",
           hjust = 0, size = 3, fontface = "bold") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 6350, color = "darkorange", size = 1) +
  annotate("text", x = 1855, y = 6353,
           label = "6,350 ft - Water salinity above 150 g/L leads to acute impacts on food supply for grebes and gulls",
           hjust = 0, size = 3, fontface = "bold") +
  geom_label_repel(aes(label = event),
                   fill = "white",
                   size = 3.5,
                   nudge_y = 25) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1850,2017,10), expand = c(0,0)) +
  ylim(6350,6450) +
  labs(x = "\nYear",
       y = "Lake Level (feet above sea level)\n") +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_cartesian(clip = "off")




Figure 1: Figure 1: Plot showing annual change in water level (feet above sea level) in Mono Lake from 1850 to 2017. Threshhold water level values impacting bird populations and two key historical events related to changing water levels are noted. Data: Mono Basin Clearinghouse



Citation
Mono Basin Clearinghouse, Mono Lake Committee. “Mono Lake Levels 1850-present”. https://www.monobasinresearch.org/data/levelyearly.php. (October 2017).

title: Text analysis of Robert Louis Stevenson's Treasure Island
description: Project completed for an assignment in Allison Horst's ESM 244 class.
contents:
Introduction
The following text analysis– with associated Rmarkdown file– explores word frequency trends and conveys the AFINN sentiment score of each chapter of Robert Louis Stevenson’s classic pirate adventure novel, Treasure Island.


hide

#read in Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson

ti <- gutenberg_download(120, mirror = "http://mirrors.xmission.com/gutenberg/")





hide

#trim the text/tidy
ti_tidy <- ti %>% 
  mutate(text = str_trim(text))





hide

#remove text outside of chapters in the novel (remove the Part structure), turn chapters into numerics 
ti_df <- ti_tidy %>% 
  slice(-(1:110)) %>% 
  mutate(chapter = case_when(
    str_detect(text, "^[0-9]+$") ~ text,
    str_detect(text, "PART[^LY]") ~ "PART",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_)) %>% 
  fill(chapter) %>% 
  filter(chapter != "PART") %>% 
  mutate(chapter = as.numeric(chapter))





hide

#tokenize, remove gb_id
ti_tokens <- ti_df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-gutenberg_id)





hide

#remove stop words
ti_nonstop_words <- ti_tokens %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words)

#word count sans stop words
ti_nonstop_counts <- ti_nonstop_words %>% 
  count(chapter, word)

#top 5 words per chapter
ti_top_5_words <- ti_nonstop_counts %>% 
  group_by(chapter) %>% 
  arrange(-n) %>% 
  slice(1:5)



Top 5 Words by Chapter
This analysis looks at the top 5 words for each chapter of Treasure Island to associate any trends… The results were unsurprising, the book is about pirates after all.


hide

#visualize the word counts
ggplot(data = ti_top_5_words, aes(x = word, y = n)) +
  geom_col(fill = "blue") +
  facet_wrap(~chapter, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_bw()




Figure 1: Figure 1: Counts of the top 5 most frequently used words in Robert Louis Stevenson’s Treasure Island by chapter.





hide

#join sentiment analysis lexicon to TI df
ti_afinn <- ti_nonstop_words %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn"))

#get afinn counts for chapter
afinn_counts <- ti_afinn %>% 
  count(chapter, value)





hide

# Plot them: 
#ggplot(data = afinn_counts, aes(x = value, y = n)) +
 # geom_col() +
  #facet_wrap(~chapter)



Sentiment Analysis using AFINN
I ran the book against the AFINN lexicon to find the mean sentiment scores per chapter. The book is a little on the dark side, especially for a book written primarily for boys.


hide

# Find the mean afinn score by chapter: 
afinn_means <- ti_afinn %>% 
  group_by(chapter) %>% 
  summarize(mean_afinn = mean(value))

#plot the afinn means
ggplot(data = afinn_means, 
       aes(x = fct_rev(as.factor(chapter)), y = mean_afinn)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(y = "Mean AFINN integer", x = "Chapter") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_bw()




Figure 2: Figure 2: Mean sentiment score for each chapter of Robert Louis Stevenson’s Treasure Island based on the AFINN sentiment lexicon. A mean score of -5 is a highly negative sentiment while a mean score of 5 is a highly positive sentiment



Word Cloud
The final product is a word cloud to present the top 100 words in the novel.


hide

#create subset of top 100 words
ti_top100 <- ti_nonstop_words %>%
  count(word) %>% 
  arrange(-n) %>% 
  slice(1:100)

# Import image for background
img.file <- here("_posts/2021-03-14-treasure-island/", "treasure_island.jpg")
img <- readJPEG(img.file)

#plot it
ti_cloud <- ggplot(data = ti_top100, aes(label = word)) +
  background_image(img) +
  geom_text_wordcloud(aes(color = n, size = n), shape = "circle") +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 10) +
  scale_color_gradientn(colors = c("goldenrod", "purple", "#660099")) +
  theme_minimal()

ti_cloud




Citation
Stevenson, R. L. (2006) Treasure Island. Project Gutenberg. [Pdf] Retrieved February 20, 2021, from Project Gutenberg Mirror, http://mirrors.xmission.com/gutenberg/.
